{
    "lab_description": "We follow research at the interface of computational chemistry, materials science, and machine learning, with a focus on atomistic simulation. Core areas: (1) Machine learning interatomic potentials (MLIPs) — equivariant graph neural networks, foundation models, transferability, training-data strategies, accuracy/cost trade-offs; representative methods include NequIP, MACE, Allegro, SchNet, GemNet, DimeNet, PaiNN, AIMNet, ANI, MatterSim, UMA, eSEN, Orb, GNoME. (2) Molecular dynamics and enhanced sampling — classical MD, ab initio MD, free-energy methods (metadynamics, umbrella sampling, replica exchange, thermodynamic integration), coarse-graining, Boltzmann generators, learned samplers. (3) Density functional theory and quantum chemistry — functionals, basis sets, GW/BSE, post-HF methods, embedding theories, automated DFT workflows, codes like VASP, CP2K, Quantum ESPRESSO, ORCA, Psi4. (4) Materials and molecular discovery — generative models for crystals and molecules, property prediction, high-throughput virtual screening, active learning, Bayesian optimization for materials, crystal structure prediction. (5) Methods and theory — equivariant neural networks (E(3)/SE(3)), diffusion and flow-matching models for atomistic systems, normalizing flows, Hamiltonian / energy-based models, geometric deep learning. We are NOT primarily interested in drug discovery (ADMET, virtual screening of drug-like libraries, protein–ligand docking), retrosynthesis, mass spectrometry, biology/protein design, or pure ML methodology that doesn't clearly transfer to atomistic systems.",

